<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="517" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,255,1146]" pageId="3" pageNumber="517">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,335,1047,1074]" pageId="3" pageNumber="517">Comments.</emphasis>
To our knowledge, no illustration or description of the female genitalia of 
<taxonomicName box="[1165,1392,1048,1074]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" genus="Epinotia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="517" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigralbana">
<emphasis box="[1165,1392,1048,1074]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="517">Epinotia nigralbana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has ever been published. 
<bibRefCitation author="Heinrich, C." box="[391,572,1084,1111]" pageId="3" pageNumber="517" pagination="1 - 216" refId="ref8068" refString="Heinrich, C. (1926) Revision of the North American moths of the subfamily Laspeyresiinae and Olethreutinae. Bulletin of the United States National Museum, 132, 1 - 216. https: // doi. org / 10.5479 / si. 03629236.132.1" type="journal article" year="1926">Heinrich (1926)</bibRefCitation>
figured the male genitalia but omitted the female. To that end, we figure the female genitalia here (
<figureCitation box="[401,485,1120,1146]" captionStart="FIGURES 7–13" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1910,1935]" captionTargetBox="[196,1391,181,1871]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[196,1391,181,1885]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 7–13. Epinotia nigralbana. 7: Backlit view of larva mining in Arbutus menziesii leaf in October; 8: Backlit view of completely mined-out Arctostaphylos leaf in March; 9: Another mined-out Arctostaphylos leaf, tied to a second leaf (below) into which the larva has begun to mine; 10: A third, vacated mine found near the previous two; 11: Pupal exuviae; 12: Reared adult female; 13: Female genitalia." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3701103" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3701103/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="517">Fig. 13</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
